01:38.867 --> 01:40.433
Hey. You got a minute?

01:40.435 --> 01:41.568
Not really.

01:41.570 --> 01:44.904
Visigoths are kind of up my butt
right now.

01:44.906 --> 01:46.840
Pause the game, Howard.

01:46.842 --> 01:48.408
“Howard”? Uh-oh.

01:48.410 --> 01:51.010
Make room, Visigoths.

01:51.546 --> 01:53.213
'Sup?

01:53.215 --> 01:55.455
We need to talk
about redecorating this place.

01:55.456 --> 01:58.385
Oh, no, not this again.
Look,

01:58.386 --> 02:01.387
I get that you grew up here
and you're attached to things

02:01.389 --> 02:02.722
looking
a certain way, but...

02:02.724 --> 02:05.363
I want this to feel
like my house, too.

02:05.364 --> 02:07.995
Oh, honey, of course
it's your house.

02:07.996 --> 02:11.197
Why else would you
be cleaning it all the time?

02:13.368 --> 02:15.268
All right.
Let's start over.

02:15.270 --> 02:16.569
I'm redecorating.

02:16.571 --> 02:18.705
The furniture,
the carpeting, the walls.

02:18.707 --> 02:21.541
I'm changing everything that
depresses me when I look at it.

02:21.543 --> 02:23.610
Try not to be one
of those things.

02:24.479 --> 02:26.179
May I say something?

02:26.181 --> 02:28.214
Is it about how I can't have
new wallpaper

02:28.216 --> 02:30.617
'cause your dad left when you
were little and your mom died?

02:30.619 --> 02:32.385
Never mind.

02:35.090 --> 02:37.390
Hello, Amy. It's Sheldon.

02:37.392 --> 02:39.692
Yeah, I-I know
that we're broken up, but

02:39.694 --> 02:41.995
I'm leaving this message because
I thought perhaps you'd like

02:41.997 --> 02:45.665
to watch me be interviewed for
a documentary about Mr. Spock.

02:45.667 --> 02:49.435
Or as I like to call it,
a Spockumentary.

02:49.437 --> 02:50.803
Yeah, I'm going to use

02:50.805 --> 02:52.906
that joke in the interview,
so try to laugh

02:52.908 --> 02:55.174
like you're hearing it
for the first time.

02:55.176 --> 02:56.976
You know, hysterically, hmm?

02:56.978 --> 03:00.880
And with a tinge of sadness
that I'm no longer in your life.

03:00.882 --> 03:03.449
I'm the one who thought
of “Spockumentary”"

03:03.451 --> 03:05.919
And I'm laughing like I did
the first time I heard it.

03:09.991 --> 03:10.990
Hello.

03:10.992 --> 03:12.058
Hey, Sheldon.

03:12.060 --> 03:13.192
This is Adam Nimoy.

03:13.194 --> 03:15.628
Nice to meet you.
Oh, it's nice to meet you.

03:15.630 --> 03:17.997
I admire your father's work
very much.

03:17.999 --> 03:20.800
It's not every day I get to meet
someone whose life's journey

03:20.802 --> 03:23.303
began in my hero's scrotum.

03:25.574 --> 03:28.508
I told you.
This guy is gold.

03:32.948 --> 03:34.347
Whatcha doing?
Oh!

03:34.349 --> 03:36.983
Making myself a bologna sandwich
like my mom used to make me

03:36.985 --> 03:39.586
after my dad left,
but before she died.

03:44.125 --> 03:45.224
Okay, listen, I'm thinking

03:45.226 --> 03:47.627
that maybe we can compromise
on the house.

03:47.629 --> 03:50.163
I'm listening.

03:50.165 --> 03:53.132
Let's just redo one room
and see how it goes.

03:53.134 --> 03:54.500
That is reasonable.

03:54.502 --> 03:56.402
But what room?

03:56.404 --> 03:58.004
How 'bout this one?

03:58.006 --> 04:02.709
No way. No, this is the room I
associate the most with my mom.

04:02.711 --> 04:04.644
Then how 'bout the bathroom?

04:04.646 --> 04:07.513
I want to change my answer.

04:07.515 --> 04:10.216
Fine. Then the dining room.

04:10.218 --> 04:12.852
I guess we didn't use it
very often.

04:12.854 --> 04:14.220
Unless we had company.

04:14.222 --> 04:16.755
Which didn't happen much
after my dad left and not at all

04:16.757 --> 04:17.470
after my mom...

04:17.494 --> 04:19.173
Great! I'm gonna go
pick out paint samples.

04:21.896 --> 04:24.030
All right, we're just gonna
have a conversation.

04:24.032 --> 04:26.366
Pretend the
camera's not here.

04:26.368 --> 04:28.501
All right.
But this better not be

04:28.503 --> 04:31.104
some elaborate scheme
to get me out of my shirt.

04:33.174 --> 04:34.540
How long have
you known Adam?

04:34.542 --> 04:35.975
A few years.
Mm-hmm.

04:35.977 --> 04:39.112
And what are you
getting him back for?

04:40.015 --> 04:41.748
Let's start with your
name and occupation.

04:41.750 --> 04:45.785
Dr. Sheldon Cooper,
theoretical physicist, Caltech.

04:45.787 --> 04:49.656
And what is your earliest memory
of the character Spock?

04:49.658 --> 04:54.293
The first episode of <i> Star Trek:</i>
<i>The Original Series</i> I ever saw

04:54.295 --> 04:56.295
was “The <i> Galileo</i> Seven.”

04:56.297 --> 04:59.732
Uh, Spock had just landed
on the planet Taurus II.

04:59.734 --> 05:02.268
Then my brother came in,
sat on my head,

05:02.270 --> 05:04.971
and said, “Eat farts.”

05:06.241 --> 05:07.740
After that day, I was hooked.

05:07.742 --> 05:09.442
On <i> Star Trek,</i>

05:09.444 --> 05:12.478
not my brother's
sphincter-based cuisine.

05:14.015 --> 05:16.916
What was it about Spock
that appealed to you?

05:16.918 --> 05:19.986
I think the same thing that
appeals to people everywhere,

05:19.988 --> 05:22.955
the dream
of a cold, rational world

05:22.957 --> 05:25.091
entirely without human emotion.

05:25.093 --> 05:27.060
Spock came

05:27.062 --> 05:29.095
from a planet governed
only by logic.

05:29.097 --> 05:31.364
You know, on Vulcan,
when your brother asks,

05:31.366 --> 05:33.900
“Why are you hitting yourself?”
the answer is,

05:33.902 --> 05:35.268
“I'm not.

05:35.270 --> 05:37.103
You're moving my arm.”

05:38.707 --> 05:39.639
To which he says,

05:39.641 --> 05:41.007
“Fascinating.”

05:41.009 --> 05:44.844
And then you both watch
educational television.

05:44.846 --> 05:46.646
Aw. When he says
things like that,

05:46.648 --> 05:48.815
I just want to hug him
and make everything better.

05:48.817 --> 05:50.850
My brother was
mean to me, too.

05:50.852 --> 05:52.518
Yeah, you probably
had it coming.

05:54.723 --> 05:56.589
Do you have
any Spock collectibles?

05:56.591 --> 05:57.657
I have many.

05:57.659 --> 06:00.093
My most treasured
is an autographed napkin

06:00.095 --> 06:02.829
given to me by my
very thoughtful friend Penny.

06:02.831 --> 06:04.163
That's her over there.

06:06.401 --> 06:08.601
Hi!

06:09.304 --> 06:10.636
Look at that.

06:10.638 --> 06:14.273
I'm in a movie,
my shirt stayed on.

06:14.275 --> 06:16.008
Can we see the napkin?

06:16.010 --> 06:17.477
Of course. Excuse me.

06:17.479 --> 06:18.978
This will just take a moment.

